<paragraph blockId="25.[151,1436,1492,1840]" pageId="25" pageNumber="226">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,273,1743,1768]" pageId="25" pageNumber="226">Notes.</emphasis>
During a brief visit to the 
<collectionCode LSID="urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:33834" box="[580,652,1744,1768]" httpUri="http://biocol.org/urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:33834" name="Museo del Instituto de Zoologia Agricola Francisco Fernandez Yepez" pageId="25" pageNumber="226">MIZA</collectionCode>
collection in 
<number box="[809,868,1744,1768]" pageId="25" pageNumber="226" value="2009.0">2009</number>
, I examined the 
<typeStatus box="[1058,1156,1743,1768]" pageId="25" pageNumber="226">holotype</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName box="[1196,1308,1744,1768]" class="Insecta" family="Protoneuridae" genus="Epipleoneura" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="25" pageNumber="226" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pallida">
<emphasis box="[1196,1308,1744,1768]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="226">E. pallida</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in order to conduct a phylogenetic analysis. Unfortunately, I neither drew the specimen nor extracted its genital ligula, in order to prevent damaging the only known specimen.
</paragraph>
